definition.value: An organic acid in which one or both oxygens of a carboxy group have been replaced by divalent sulfur.
An ester of a carboxylic acid, R(1)C(=O)OR(2), where R(1) = H or organyl and R(2) = organyl.
A radioactive metallic element discovered in 1898 by Marie Sklodowska Curie and named after her home country, Poland (Latin Polonia).
An atom belonging to one of the main groups (found in the s- and p- blocks) of the periodic table.
The principal alkaloid of the plant family Calycanthaceae.
A divalent group formed from an alkane by removal of two hydrogen atoms from the same carbon atom, the free valencies of which are part of a double bond.
A group derived from an arene by removal of a hydrogen atom from a ring carbon atom.
A bivalent group derived from an arene by removal of a hydrogen atom from each of two ring carbon atoms.
A cobalt group element atom of atomic number 45.
